The International Symposium on Aviation Psychology (ISAP) is a biennial conference that brings researchers and engineers together with pilots, air traffic controllers, aircraft maintenance workers, and other aviation industry personnel. The symposium aims to create a safer and more efficient airspace by applying the findings of basic psychology and cognitive neuroscience to aviation systems. The research showcased helps designers and managers:

build technology that lets frontline aviation personnel perform their jobs safely, efficiently, and effectively, and 
select and train human operators as well as possible for their roles.


By establishing design principles on fundamental knowledge of performance and cognition, the research presented at ISAP also brings benefit to domains of application beyond aviation, including medicine, driving, and defense.

The 21st ISAP was held online, May 18-21, 2021, and drew 237 attendees from 31 countries. International attendees comprised 34% of registrants, and 32% of attendees were students. Non-student attendees represented the academic, government, and industry sectors.

Presentations at the 2021 ISAP covered themes including

Advanced Air Mobility; 
Airspace and Air Traffic Management;
 Aviation Interface Design; 
Education; 
Exploring Methods to Collect and Analyze Human Contributions to Safety; 
Human-Machine Teaming; 
Organizational Safety and Culture; 
Selection of Air Traffic Controllers and Pilots; 
Skills Degradation and Assessment; 
Skills Training; 
Teamwork and Multiteam Coordination; and, 
Weather Hazards Affecting General Aviation Safety. 


Other meeting sessions included a Best Student Paper Competition, discussion panels of aviation practitioners and researchers, and keynote talks on cognitive neuroscience for aviation and on human-machine teaming.

